<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK President on Upcoming Talks With Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK President on Upcoming Talks With Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306150194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1332 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 13 Jun (TANJUG) -- The fact that the Croatian 
delegation [to negotiations with the Krajina Serbs] accepted 
Plitvice as a venue for talks on economic cooperation with the 
Krajina delegation is a kind of recognition of the republic of 
Serb Krajina [RSK], said RSK President Milan Martic at a news 
conference in Knin today. 
  He said that the protocol for the talks was agreed with 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces]. Krajina official bodies will 
provide security at the talks. The official Krajina insignia 
will be displayed in Plitvice except in the conference hall. 
  A single Croatian journalist will be allowed to attend the 
talks. This is based on the principle of reciprocity since one 
Krajina reporter was present at the recent talks in the Russian 
Embassy in Zagreb. 
  Asked about the implementation of the Zagreb agreement by 
the 
Republic of Croatia, Martic said that he discussed this with 
Butrus-Ghali's special envoy, Yasushi Akashi, and with 
UNPROFOR's head of civil affairs in Sector South, Enrico 
Aguillar. Martic said he was given guarantees that Croatia will 
implement the provisions of the [Zagreb] agreement before the 
Plitvice round of talks. 
  President Martic also commented on the latest statements by 
Croatian officials about the reintegration of Krajina into 
Croatia and their threats about a new war. We are closely 
following the situation and we are ready to respond to a 
possible Croatian reaction, Martic said, adding that he received 
guarantees in Geneva that such behavior by Croatia will be 
rigorously sanctioned by international factors. 
  The talks in Plitvice will primarily deal with economic 
issues based on the principle of reciprocity. Certain 
humanitarian issues should also be discussed, such as pensions 
blocked by the Republic of Croatia immediately after the 
outbreak of the war. In the long term there can be no permanent 
cooperation with Croatia without annulment of UN Security 
Council resolution 820 which left the Serb nation in the RSK in 
a specific kind of isolation, Martic said, adding that there can 
be no political and economic cooperation without the equality of 
the partners. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

