Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Receives Herceg-Bosna Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman Receives Herceg-Bosna Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206123594 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1100 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Zagreb yesterday President Tudjman received the 
leaderships of the Croatian republic of Herceg-Bosna and the 
Croatian Democratic Union [HDZ] of Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Croat 
deputies from the Constitutional Assembly of the Federation of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, stated the presidential office on Saturday 
evening. 
  The Croatian president and his guests discussed the further 
implementation of the Washington agreements and confirmed that 
it was very important to make efforts for implementing the 
agreement regarding the organization of the B-H Federation and 
the creation of a confederation with the Republic of Croatia. 
Undertaking these efforts, the Croatian people in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina should remain united in order to achieve its 
political aims and the strategic interests of the Croatian 
state. On this occasion President Tudjman announced his 
forthcoming visit to Sarajevo in an effort to contribute to the 
implementation of the Washington agreement. 
  Last night's meeting was also attended by Croatian Foreign 
Minister Mate Granic, Defense Minister Gojko Susak, Ivan Milas, 
president of the HDZ deputies' club in the assembly, Ivan 
Aralica, deputy spokesman of the Chamber of Counties, Ivic 
Pasalic, HDZ member and the president's internal affairs 
adviser, and Miomir Zuzul, Croatian Ambassador to the United 
Nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

