<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   DSK Admits Albania Guiding Movement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DSK Admits Albania Guiding Movement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006190394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1725 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, June 10 (TANJUG) -- Fehmi Agani, second in 
command in the Democratic Alliance of Kosovo (DSK) party of the 
Albanian separatists in the southern Serbian province of 
Kosovo-Metohija (Kosmet), openly admitted on Friday that the 
Republic of Albania was guiding the activities of the political 
movement of the Albanians in the province. 
  The DSK vice-chairman told a press conference that "identity 
of stands between the DSK and Albania" was reaffirmed on 
Thursday during the talk between DSK Chairman Ibrahim Rugova and 
Albanian President Sali Berisha. 
  Agani said that "consultations and coordination of DSK 
activities with Albania were one of the major results of the 
political movement of the Albanians in Kosovo-Metohija." Agani 
admitted that Albania's "strong support" was the major factor of 
success of the struggle for the fulfillment of DSK demands. 
  The Albanian separatists have been trying for decades to 
secede Kosovo-Metohija from Serbia, i.e. the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.), using conventional terrorist methods and 
attacking members of the police and the army. The F.R.Y.'s 
attempts to develop good-neighbourly relations with neighbouring 
Republic of Albania remain unsuccessful because Tirana is 
persistently and openly supporting the separatist movement in 
Kosmet, thus meddling with the F.R.Y.'s internal affairs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31720 </DOCNO>
