<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Meets With FKGP Chairman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Meets With FKGP Chairman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006144294 Budapest MTI in English 1310 GMT 10 Jun 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1006144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 10 Jun (MTI) -- Hungarian President Arpad 
Goncz on Friday continued his meetings with the leaders of the 
parliamentary parties, and received the chairman of the 
Independent Smallholders' Party (FKGP), Jozsef Torgyan. At a 
press conference following the meeting, Torgyan said he mainly 
called the president's attention to the fact that the dominance 
of executive power could make parliamentary democracy, which is 
based on a system of brakes and counter-weights represented by 
the opposition, illusory. 
  In this context Torgyan said the executive power had waged a 
campaign against his party over the last four years, accusing 
the FKGP with various charges, freezing its state support, and 
making efforts to break it up through smallholders created by 
the power. The FKGP chairman also said his family was exposed 
to harassment. 
  Torgyan said he considered it necessary to relate this to 
the 
president because, in principle, there is a danger that an even 
stronger parliamentary dictatorship will come about alongside 
the ever more powerful executive power, in the wake of the 
election results. The danger of a one-party like system is 
further increased by the fact that, according to Torgyan, the 
revival of middle-level cadres of the former state party, the 
Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party, can be experienced 
nationwide. 
  Although the Hungarian Socialist Party [MSZP], which won the 
elections, and the Alliance of Free Democrats [SZDSZ], which 
came in second, are endeavouring to work out a system of 
guarantees, Torgyan said neither the Hungarian Democratic Forum 
[MDF], nor the Christian Democratic People's party can be a 
genuine opposition force under the current circumstances. As 
regards the Federation of Young Democrats, Torgyan said the 
future will decide whether the party will be a liberal, or a 
popular-national force. Thus there is no other prominent 
opposition force apart from the Independent Smallholders' Party. 
  The FKGP chairman also said his party would ensure a greater 
role for the president of the Republic, in order to 
counter-balance the executive power. For instance, as regards 
the media, the FKGP would empower the president with the 
appointment right of media leaders that would not require 
counter-initialling by the prime minister. 
  Another element that would, according to the FKGP's intents, 
intensify the president's position would be his direct election 
by the people. According to the FKGP, it cannot be allowed that 
the media be subordinated to the government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31759 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu114__a94022" </HT>


