<H3> <TI>   Election Disagreement Sent to Supreme Court </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Disagreement Sent to Supreme Court </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1306201494 Budapest MTI in English 1851 GMT 13 Jun 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1306201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, June 13 (MTI) -- Contrary to original 
plans, the National Election Committee could not declare the 
final official result of the parliamentary elections today, as 
Mayor Gyula Varga of Kapuvar (W Hungary), a candidate of the 
Alliance of Free Democrats (SZDSZ), has turned to the Supreme 
Court to request a repeated re-count of valid and invalid votes 
cast in the sixth constituency -- west Hungarian 
Gyor-Moson-Sopron county. 
  As was reported earlier, Varga won the mandate in the May 29 
elections by 10 votes, ahead of the Hungarian Democratic Forum 
[MDF] candidate Gyorgy Rasko, who subsequently asked for a 
re-count by the National Election Committee. Based on this 
re-count, in which the committee re-classified several invalid 
votes as valid, and invalidated several valid votes, Rasko ended 
up in first place. 
  According to Varga's information, there were many ballots 
among those examined by the committee and classified valid which 
should be invalid under the electoral law. 
  If the Supreme Court decides on the matter this Thursday, 
the 
National Election Committee will declare the final official 
result of the elections that evening. 

</TEXT>

