<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   HZDS To Sue President for Constitution Breach </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    HZDS To Sue President for Constitution Breach </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1306183094 Prague CTK in English 1753 GMT 13 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1306183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, June 13 (CTK) -- Former Premier 
Vladimir Meciar's Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) will 
lodge a complaint with the Constitutional Court against 
President Michal Kovac because he allegedly breached his 
constitutional duty to call referendum, Tibor Cabaj, chairman of 
the HZDS deputies group, said today. The Slovak Constitution 
stipulates that the president can be dismissed if he fails to 
observe his constitutional duties. 
  In February the HZDS organized a petition campaign in 
support 
of a referendum through which they wanted to resolve the 
political crisis. The citizens had to decide on three issues: 
calling early elections, exclusion of the "renegade deputies" 
from parliament (Meciar's cabinet fell because some of the HZDS 
deputies had left the party which lost the majority in 
parliament), and explanation of the origin of money used in 
privatization. However, in March Kovac refused to call the 
referendum because the 350,000 signatures, required by the 
Constitution, had not been collected, as the Presidential Office 
had found. 
  In the meantime, the parliament has dismissed Meciar's 
cabinet and set the early elections for this autumn. The HZDS 
has checked again the collected signatures and found out that 
out of 422,054, 372,054 were valid so that Kovac ought to have 
called the referendum, Cabaj said. 
  Katarina Tothova, the justice minister in Meciar's cabinet, 
pointed to a contradiction in the statement by the Presidential 
Office which had said in March that only 232,957 were authentic, 
while at present it acknowledged validity of almost 325,000 
signatures. She noted that law which had been in force in 
February, did not stipulate that exact address and 
identification number were necessary, as required now by the 
amended law on referendum which had been passed last week. 
Tothova also denied an allegation by Peter Weiss, chairman of 
the Democratic Left Party (SDL), that the HZDS was preparing 
another referendum which would shorten Kovac's five-year term. 
Kovac was elected last year. "I do not know anything about 
another petition committee," she added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

