<H3> <TI>   Moravcik on Ethnic Minorities, Law on Signs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik on Ethnic Minorities, Law on Signs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006154094 Prague CTK in English 1221 GMT 10 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1006154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava June 10 (CTK) -- Premier Jozef Moravcik 
told Slovak Radio today he was convinced that Hungarian and 
Slovak positions regarding their ethnic minorities would come 
closer. "We cannot be indifferent to Slovaks abroad, as the 
Hungarian Government cannot be indifferent to Hungarians living 
outside Hungary," Moravcik added. The ethnic Hungarians in 
Slovakia number about 560,000 people, or 11 percent of 
Slovakia's population. 
  The ethnic minorities issues should be involved in the 
Hungarian-Slovak agreement, Moravcik said. This was agreed upon 
during his recent meeting with executive deputy chairman of the 
Hungarian Socialist Party Imre Szekeres, he added. 
  Moravcik noted that the present government was ready to 
settle the "signpost" law on the bilingual names for towns and 
villages in the ethnic language, rejected last week for the 
second time in parliament. This time the signpost law should be 
submitted as a private member's bill, only on condition that it 
will be submitted by a simple majority of Slovak deputies, 
Moravcik explained. If the law were rejected for the third 
times, it would not be "pleasant" because of domestic and 
international situation, he said. 

</TEXT>

