<F P=101> Bosnia-Herzegovina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mazowiecki Accuses Serbs of `Terror' in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mazowiecki Accuses Serbs of `Terror' in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006203394 Warsaw PAP in English 2016 GMT 10 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1006203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, June 10 -- In his latest report, U.N. human 
rights commission's envoy to former Yugoslavia Tadeusz 
Mazowiecki accused Serbs of terror during their offensive on the 
Muslim enclave of Gorazde last April. The report on human 
rights in former Yugoslavia accuses Bosnian Serbs of 
deliberately directing artillery fire on hospitals, performing 
mass executions, expelling civilians, destroying houses and 
killing livestock during the month-long attack on eastern 
Bosnia. It also quotes eyewitnesses of rapes by Serbian 
soldiers. 
  Mazowiecki wrote in his report that there were also cases of 
Muslim violation of the Serbs' rights but on a much smaller 
scale. He appealed for a more significant presence of U.N. 
peace-keeping forces in the Gorazde area which would "reduce the 
risk of further Serbian assaults." 

</TEXT>

