<H3> <TI>   New FNM Chairman Ceska Profiled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New FNM Chairman Ceska Profiled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006195894 Prague CTK in English 1856 GMT 10 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1006195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague June 10 (CTK) -- New National Property Fund 
(FNM) Chairman Roman Ceska today said he considered his most 
important task to be the stabilisation of the "unbearable" 
situation in the fund. He told CTK he did not think that his 
appointment could jeopardise the fund's activity. "I do not 
believe that people will leave the fund due to my appointment," 
he said, adding that his primary task will be to put an end to 
long-lasting feelings of uncertainty among the fund's employees. 
  In his opinion, an FNM chairman should devote all his time 
to 
management, not politics. He described his predecessor Tomas 
Jezek as a "remarkable political figure." 
  Ceska was born in Plzen, western Bohemia, on January 29, 
1964. After finishing studies at a grammar school in Plzen he 
left for Prague where he graduated from the Prague School of 
Economics. He started working in the Czechoslovak Academy of 
Sciences Economic Institute in 1990, and when the Privatisation 
Ministry was created he became an advisor to then minister Tomas 
Jezek. After the parliamentary elections in 1992 Ceska was 
appointed deputy privatisation minister. 

</TEXT>

