<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Cited on Assigning Powers of Senate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Cited on Assigning Powers of Senate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1206171894 Prague CTK in English 1433 GMT 12 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1206171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, June 12 (CTK) -- President Vaclav Havel 
said today the current state where the undissolvable Chamber of 
Deputies was taking over the powers of the yet unformed Senate 
could not last forever since "it is really dangerous." In his 
regular Sunday radio programme "Talks in Lany" Havel said that 
either the Senate had to be set up in compliance with the 
Constitution, or some other constitutional solution had to be 
found. 
  He was reacting to the fact that the Chamber of Deputies 
failed on June 2 to pass a bill on elections to the Senate and 
to the Chamber, thus making senatorial elections planned for the 
autumn probably impossible. Elections to the Chamber are to be 
held in 1996. 
  Reacting to Friday's [9 June] proposal from the coalition 
Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL) 
on the division of the Senate's powers between the Chamber of 
Deputies, the president and possibly the government, Havel said: 
"Every additional power needs more work for my Office which 
already now would need more employees than it has. The question 
is what is correct." 
  But he added that "the powers which the Senate was to have, 
must go somewhere." It would be logical if the president's right 
to return laws to the Chamber would be extended by the right to 
accompany the returned law with comments which the valid 
Constitution does not guarantee for him, Havel said. 

</TEXT>

