<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Citizens Leaning Toward Political Center </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Citizens Leaning Toward Political Center </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1306110294 Prague CTK in English 1006 GMT 13 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1306110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague June 13 (CTK) -- The majority of Czech 
citizens declare themselves supporters of the political centre, 
a poll conducted by the Institute for Public Opinion Research 
(IVVM) on April 28 to May 6 among 946 people over 15 showed. 
Although most Czechs are still orientated to the right, a shift 
towards the centre or left of the centre continues, the poll 
revealed. According to the IVVM, such development is connected 
with a repeated fall in voter preferences of the Civic 
Democratic Party (ODS), the strongest party in the government 
coalition. 
  Only five percent of those polled declared themselves 
supporters of extreme right parties and only 2 percent said they 
support extreme left parties. Thirty-three percent of the 
respondents see themselves to be at the political centre. 
  Followers of the Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia 
(KSCM), the Left Bloc Party (LB) and the Democratic Left Party 
(SDL) are mostly left-orientated. As regards the Czech Social 
Democratic Party (CSSD) none of its potential voters declared 
themselves supporters of extreme left while 75 percent of them 
support either left of the centre or centre parties. 
  The ODS's potential voters traditionally stand unambiguously 
on the right spectrum of the political scene, while followers of 
the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) and the Christian Democratic 
Union- Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL), both government 
coalition parties, mostly declared themselves supporters the 
right-centre spectrum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

