<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Favors Unification With Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Leader Favors Unification With Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506144194 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1506144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dragoljub Stankic] </F>
  [Text] At a regular news conference of the Democratic Party 
of Serbia, party leader Vojislav Kostunica spoke about the 
former Bosnia-Herzegovina. Dragoljub Stankic reports: 
  [Stankic] It is positive that the truce is being observed, 
but many issues remain open, Vojislav Kostunica said. The 
acceptance of the proposed delineation and the 51-49 percent 
division is connected with other formulas, above all the quality 
of the territory that is being offered. According to Kostunica, 
the issue of the Serbian access to the sea, the width of the 
so-called corridor through the Sava basin region, the gray 
zones, and so forth are still contentious. 
  Kostunica said that despite all this there are many reasons 
for optimism while waiting for the final denouement. If the 
future of the Muslim-Croatian federation is seen in a joint 
state with Croatia, then, Kostunica said, many contentious 
issues on the Serbian side will be solved much faster if the 
Srpska republic and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia become 
one state. 

</TEXT>

