<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Leader Stresses Property Protection </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajina Leader Stresses Property Protection </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506170794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1646 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 15 (TANJUG) -- The president of the 
Republic of Serb Krajina (RSK), Milan Martic, asked the 
co-chairmen of the conference on the former Yugoslavia, Lord 
David Owen and Thorwald Stoltenberg, to urge that RSK property 
is protected in all new states created in the territory of the 
ex-Yugoslavia and in third countries. Martic said that RSK 
representatives have so far not taken part in the work of the 
international conference on the former Yugoslavia regarding 
succession issues. Martic said that no newly-created state in 
the territory of ex-Yugoslavia, including RSK, can be excluded 
from the succession talks. He asked Owen and Stoltenberg to 
mediate in the resolution of the problem of the deposits of RSK 
citizens in Ljubljanska Banka, one of the major commercial banks 
in the former Yugoslavia which was located in Ljubljana, capital 
of Slovenia, to prevent Slovenia from transferring the funds to 
the account of the state of Croatia. 
  RSK was proclaimed by the local Serbs in 1991 in their 
ancestral lands in Croatia in response to its violent secession 
from the former Yugoslav federation and the downgrading of their 
status. RSK is a U.N. protected area since March 1992. 

</TEXT>

