<H3> <TI>   Croatia-Krajina Talks Hinge on Reporters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croatia-Krajina Talks Hinge on Reporters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606095994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0901 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Plitvice, 16 Jun (TANJUG) -- If talks between 
delegations of the republic of Serb Krajina and the Republic of 
Croatia take place, initially scheduled for 16 and 17 June, they 
will start at about 1600 today, a TANJUG reporter has learned in 
Plitvice. 
  The negotiations were expected to start this morning but, as 
is known, they were postponed because the Croatian side demanded 
that the number of attending reporters be higher than the number 
admitted in Zagreb. The Croatian side is demanding that five 
Croatian reporters and all Zagreb-based U.S. reporters come. 
Moreover, the reporters should be enabled to travel by car via 
the border crossing of Turanj near Karlovac. 
  Letters were exchanged this morning, via the UN Protection 
Forces [UNPROFOR], between the governments of the republic of 
Serb Krajina and the Republic of Croatia, thus bringing about a 
possibility of the negotiations taking place at 1600. As is 
known, the negotiations are expected to focus on economic issues. 
  One of the contested issues, as demanded by the government 
of 
the republic of Serb Krajina, is the withdrawal of Croatian 
forces from western Slavonia, Mt. Velebit, and some other areas 
in keeping with an agreement signed on 29 March this year in 
Zagreb. 

</TEXT>

