<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry on Upcoming FYROM Census </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry on Upcoming FYROM Census </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506145294 Sofia BTA in English 1325 GMT 15 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1506145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, June 15 (BTA) -- European standards 
concerning the free expression of national identity are much 
higher than those operative in Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] which are likely to be applied 
in the forthcoming census there, Foreign Ministry spokesman 
Radko Vlaykov told a news conference here today. The official 
documents on the forthcoming census (to be taken June 21-July 5) 
mention a choice of seven nationalities, including even Turkish 
and Egyptian, but no Bulgarian. 
  The Foreign Ministry spokesman said that prior to the census 
the government of Macedonia should take the necessary steps to 
secure free expression for all its citizens, in line with 
European standards. Bulgaria will take a stand on the results 
accordingly. 
  Bulgaria follows with great interest the process of 
democratization in Macedonia and supports its efforts to join 
the community of free and democratic states, Mr. Vlaykov pointed 
out. He reminded that Bulgaria was the first country to 
recognize the independence of Macedonia and clearly declared its 
willingness for close cooperation. It makes efforts to assist 
Macedonia's integration with the international community and the 
recognition of its independence. Bulgaria's efforts to help 
Macedonia overcome its economic difficulties are no secret, 
either, he added. 
  Only 1,500 Bulgarians were registered in Macedonia in the 
latest census. In the forms for the new one the Bulgarian 
nationality has not been included at all. The previous census 
was boycotted by the Albanians for the same reason. Now, unlike 
Bulgarians, they have been included in the forms. Mr. Ilija 
Ilijevski, leader of the Human Rights Party in Macedonia, told 
reporters in Sofia last week that Bulgarians will be deprived of 
the right to free expression of their national identity. He 
also pointed out that the census will be conducted in conditions 
of long-lasting violation of the human rights of Bulgarians in 
Macedonia and that the results will not be objective and 
reliable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31876 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu116__a94003" </HT>


