FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1406135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 14 June (MTI) -- Hungarian Prime Minister 
Peter Boross sent a telegram to Austrian Chancellor Franz 
Vranitzky expressing his good wishes on the occasion that the 
vast majority of the Austrian people opted to join the European 
Union. 
  Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky on Monday [13 June] 
congratulated by letter Austrian counterpart Alois Mock, on the 
referendum result. The letter, sent to MTI on Tuesday [14 
June], says, "The outcome of the referendum is a clear signal to 
the whole of Europe. Both Austria and the Union stand to benefit 
from Austria's membership, which will also promote European 
unification. To Hungary, it is particularly important that 
neighboring Austria will be in the European Union." 
  Jeszenszy believes Hungary will be able to count on 
Austria's 
support in the EU. Hungary, which has applied to join, is 
confident that both countries will jointly help build a single 
Europe. 

</TEXT>

